03960nam a22004935i 9780226780979DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267809797 a10.7208/97802267809792doi  a(DE-B1597)588982  a(OCoLC)1259590384  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aKrause, Monika, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModel Cases :bOn Canonical Research Objects and Sites /cMonika Krause. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b8 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Material Research Objects and Privileged Material Research Objects -- t2 How Material Research Objects Are Selected -- t3 Model Cases and the Dream of Collective Methods -- t4 How Subfield Categories Shape Knowledge -- t5 The Schemas of Social Theory -- t6 The Model Cases of Global Knowledge -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe all know scientists study a predictable set of organisms when performing research, whether they be mice, fruit flies, or less commonly known but widely used species of snail or worm. But when we think of the so-called humanistic social sciences, we envision a different kind of research attuned to historical power relations or the unique experiences of a social group. In Model Cases, sociologist Monika Krause uncovers the ways the humanities and social sciences are shaped by and dependent on a set of canonical research objects of their own, often in unacknowledged ways. Krause shows that some research objects are studied repeatedly and shape the understanding of more general categories in disproportionate ways. For instance, Chicago comes to be the touchstone for studies of the modern city or Michel Foucault's analysis of Bentham's prison a guiding light for understanding contemporary power relations. Moving through classic cases in the social sciences, Krause reveals the ways canonical examples and sites have shaped research and theory, showing how they can both help and harm the production of knowledge. In the end, she argues, model cases have great potential to serve scholarship—as long as they are acknowledged and examined with acuity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCase method. 0aSocial sciencesxMethodology. 0aSocial sciencesxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aresearch, researcher, objects, periods, regions, social sciences, humanities, scholarly, academic, academia, ideological, convenience, history, historicist, development, french revolution, citizenship, europe, european, wartime, politics, political, modernity, analysis, case study, specialization, schemas, global, international, classroom, educational.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226780979423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226780979/original  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles